ERRORS IN THE MARGINAL REFERENCES.

These are not uncommon, and the second edition—which was pub- lished at Antwerp in 1597, therefore after Ayala's death—gives very little help in detecting them. The most usual error is in a number, say of a Book of Livy or of a Causa in the Decretum: sometimes a passage is assigned by mistake to the Digest instead of to the Code: sometimes a small, but disconcerting slip is made in the name of a Title in the Digest or the Code (thus de non foen. is given for de nautico ferm).

It is not proposed to give a list of such errors as have been found: instead, the translator has corrected them in the margin of the transla- tion. In the few cases where he rernains baffled (whether by an error or by an obscurity) he has printed the reference as it stands in the orig- inal (see, e. g., note a, p. 10οα, vol. 1, and note a, p. 219, vol. 1.).
